    • registerAll

      public static void registerAll(@Nonnull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers JDKGDXDS' classes with the given Json object, allowing it to read and write JDKGDXDS types.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have serializers registered for all JDKGDXDS types.

    • getNumeralBase

      public static com.github.tommyettinger.ds.support.Base getNumeralBase()
      Gets the numeral system, also called radix or base, used by some methods here to encode numbers. If it hasn't been changed, the default this uses is Base.BASE36, because it is fairly compact.
      Returns:
      the Base system this uses, which is always non-null.

    • setNumeralBase

      public static void setNumeralBase(com.github.tommyettinger.ds.support.Base base)
      Sets the numeral system, also called radix or base, used by some methods here to encode numbers. This is most likely to be used with Base.scrambledBase(EnhancedRandom) to obfuscate specific numbers, typically random seeds, put into readable JSON files. The methods this affects are all related to registering EnhancedRandom and its implementations, RandomXS128, and AtomicLong. If this hasn't been called, the default this uses is Base.BASE36, because it is fairly compact.
      Parameters:
      base - a non-null Base system

    • registerBinaryHeap

      public static void registerBinaryHeap(@Nonnull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers BinaryHeap with the given Json object, so BinaryHeap can be written to and read from JSON. It may be problematic to register a custom serializer for the Node items of the BinaryHeap, so it's recommended that you don't; the output is more verbose with the default serialization, but it works.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered

    • registerAtomicLong

      public static void registerAtomicLong(@Nonnull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers AtomicLong with the given Json object, so AtomicLong can be written to and read from JSON. This primarily matters if you intend to read and/or write Random objects or their subclasses without registering a custom serializer for them. Although the EnhancedRandom implementations in jdkgdxds have custom serializers here already, and don't need this method to be called, other classes that extend Random are likely to need this if you ever run on Java 16 or higher.
      Surprisingly, this method is compatible with GWT, even though most concurrent code doesn't work there.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered

    • registerEnhancedRandom

      public static void registerEnhancedRandom(@Nonnull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers EnhancedRandom with the given Json object, so EnhancedRandom can be written to and read from JSON. This also registers DistinctRandom, LaserRandom, TricycleRandom, FourWheelRandom, Xoshiro256StarStarRandom, and StrangerRandom, plus AtomicLong because some subclasses of Random need it.
      Interfaces aren't usually serializable like this, but because each of the EnhancedRandom serializers uses a specific format shared with what this uses, and that format identifies which class is used, it works here. Well, it works as long as the EnhancedRandom implementation you are serializing or deserializing was itself registered with this. You don't have to worry about that for any of the jdkgdxds EnhancedRandom types.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered

    • registerRandomXS128

      public static void registerRandomXS128(@Nonnull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers RandomXS128 with the given Json object, so RandomXS128 can be written to and read from JSON. Note that RandomXS128 is not a jdkgdxds EnhancedRandom, and so registering this won't allow you to read RandomXS128 objects from EnhancedRandom fields. This serializer is here to reduce the hassle when you do want to serialize a RandomXS128, because on Java 16 and higher, RandomXS128 would need some extra steps for Json to be able to read some fields from it.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered
